<div class="article-wrapper">
	
	
	
		<div class="article">
	
		
		

			
				
				<h1>
					
						BEA 2014: Why Tor Dumped DRM
					
					
				</h1>
				
				
				<div class="article-byline">
					By Andrew Albanese			
					
						 | 
					
				</div>
				<div class="article-date">
					May 29, 2014
				</div>
			

			<div id="share-inline" class="inline no-paper-copy" tag="div" data-jsclass="share" data-ajaxSrc="components/share.html" data-deliver="ajax" data-article="62577" data-url="/pw/by-topic/industry-news/bea/article/62577-bea-2014-why-drm-is-the-problem.html" data-path="/by-topic/industry-news/bea/article/62577-bea-2014-why-drm-is-the-problem.html" data-inline="false" data-comments="true" data-topic="98"></div>

			
			
							
				
			
			
			<div class="article-body">
				<p class=article>The subject of DRM and e-books has been a hot topic in recent years, and in an afternoon talk at the opening International Digital Publishing Forum (IDPF) at BEA, Tor Books founder Tom Doherty talked about the publisher&rsquo;s 2012 decision <a href="/pw/by-topic/digital/content-and-e-books/article/51659-tor-forge-plans-drm-free-e-books-by-july.html" target="_blank">to dump DRM from its e-books.</a></p><p class=article>&ldquo;After discussing it with authors and readers, it became pretty clear that DRM was not much of a problem for the sophisticated pirate, but it was, however, a meaningful problem and an annoyance to many of our readers,&rdquo; Doherty told the audience. &ldquo;So, we went all in.&rdquo;</p><div data-jsClass="articleRelated" data-ajaxSrc="components/article-related.html" data-deliver="ajax" id="articleRelatedEmbed" data-try-photo="1" tag="div" class="embed-table-left" style="width:213px;" data-article="62577"></div><p class=article>Although piracy continues to be an issue for Tor, and the publishing industry in general, Doherty acknowledged, dumping DRM on its entire list has paid off.</p><p class=article>&ldquo;So far, the lack of DRM has not increased the number of Tor e-books online illegally, nor has it visibly hurt our sales,&rdquo; Doherty said. &ldquo;We decided that if we play fair with [our customer] they will play fair with us. And, you know, it&#39;s working.&rdquo;</p><p class=article>While those looking for numbers or more concrete evidence about Doherty and Tor&rsquo;s DRM experience were likely disappointed, Doherty&rsquo;s broader message about DRM was much-needed, and well-timed. Good publishing, he stressed, is about fostering a community.</p><p class=article>And not just a community of publishers and booksellers, Doherty stressed, but librarians, authors, readers, teachers, fans, and critics.</p><p class=article>"Books create the conversations we hear and are part of, so it&#39;s important that we make these conversations critical to any decision we make in our publishing programs.&rdquo;</p><p class=article>Doherty said the Sci-fi community has always talked in the physical space, and shared books and ideas. Now, they also do so in the digital space and DRM, he felt, was throttling that; the issue of DRM, he added, had become a &ldquo;central concern&rdquo; at Tor. &ldquo;Authors need to connect,&rdquo; he noted. &ldquo;And barriers, whether DRM or something else, disrupt these connections.&rdquo;</p><p class=article>The "community" approach has worked well for Tor, Doherty, said, <a href="http://www.tor.com/blogs/2014/05/announcing-torcom-the-imprint" target="_blank">taking the opportunity to announce a new DRM-free imprint&mdash;Tor.com</a>&mdash;which will be dedicated to publishing novellas, shorter novels, and serializations. Doherty said he sees digital as a way to &ldquo;reclaim the length of the novella, a format that I have always felt is a natural form to science fiction,&rdquo; and was once &ldquo;very important when magazines were dominant in SciFi readership, but which has almost disappeared as that market declined.&rdquo;</p><p class=article>In perhaps his most cogent observations, though, Doherty spoke of &ldquo;the bigger issue&rdquo; with DRM: the dangerous &ldquo;lock-ins&rdquo; that it can impose.<br /> <br />&ldquo;Many of our customers have seen what can happen when vendors control proprietary DRM formats,&rdquo; he said. &ldquo;It hasn&rsquo;t happened much in the world of books, but it has happened in gaming, music, and video, when a business went belly up or simply stopped supporting DRM formats, leaving customers with big stacks of content they had paid for, which only runs on devices now orphaned.&rdquo;</p><p class=article>Of course, it is not just consumers that can suffer. The lock-ins can also affect publishers. In fact, <a href="/pw/by-topic/columns-and-blogs/cory-doctorow/article/51292-cory-doctorow-a-whip-to-beat-us-with.html" target="_blank">DRM plays a part in the current Amazon/Hachette battle</a>. After all, Amazon is not just a retailer, but a DRM-protected platform. Thus, Kindle owners are in effect Amazon customers first&mdash;a consumer cannot walk away from Amazon and take their purchased Kindle books with them to a competing platform.</p>
			</div>
	
		
		
				<div 
			tag="div" 
			id="also-on-pw" 
			data-jsclass="alsoOnPw" 
